MYCOPLASMA MORTALITY, CAPTIVE ALLIGATORS - FLORIDA (02)
=======================================================
[See: Mycoplasma mortality, captive alligators - Florida 970307235223]
From: Kent A. Vliet, Ph.D
Date: Sun, 09 Mar 1997
Via: Steve Grenard <grenard@con2.com>

The organism is a new species and is provisionally named Mycoplasma
lacerti. First citations are:
Brown, D.R., Clippinger, T.L., Helmick, K.E., Schumacker, I.M., Bennett,
R.A., Johnson, C.M., Vliet, K.A., Jacobson, E.R. and Brown, M.B. 1996.
Mycoplasma isolation during a fatal epizootic of captive alligators
(Alligator mississippiensis) in Florida. International Organization of
Mycoplasmology Letters 4:42-43.
Clippinger, T.L., Bennett, R.A., Johnson, C.A., Vliet, K.A., Jacobson,
E.R., Brown, D.R., and Brown, M.B. 1996. Mycoplasma epizootic in a herd
of bull alligators (Alligator mississippiensis). Proc. Amer. Assoc. Zoo
Vet. Ann. Conf. Pp. 230-234.
The organism was identified by nucleotide sequence analysis of the 16S rRna
gene and compared to that of M. crocodyli from Nile crocodiles in Zimbabwe.
Although quite similar, these two organisms appear to be distinct.
--
